{{ Globular cluster | | name = [http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/sim-id.pl?protocol=html&Ident=M12 M12] | image = [[image:Messier12.jpg|280px]] |caption=Messier 12, from ''[[w:2MASS|2MASS]]'' | epoch = [[w:J2000|J2000]] | class = IX | constellation = [[w:Ophiuchus|Ophiuchus]] | ra = {{RA|16|47|14.52}}<ref name="simbad">{{cite web | title=SIMBAD Astronomical Database | work=Results for NGC 6218 | url=http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/Simbad | accessdate=2006-11-15}}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|-01|56|52.1}}<ref name="simbad" /> | dist_ly = 16.0 [[w:light-year|kly]] | dist_pc = 4.9 [[w:parsec|kpc]] | appmag_v = +7.68<ref name="simbad" /> | size_v = 16&prime;.0 | mass_kg = | mass_msol = | radius_ly = 37.2 ly<ref>distance &times; sin( diameter_angle / 2 ) = 37.2 ly. radius</ref> | v_hb = | age = | notes = | names = [[w:New General Catalogue|NGC]] 6218<ref name="simbad" /> }}
'''Messier 12''' or '''M 12''' (also designated '''NGC 6218''') is a [[w:globular cluster]] in the [[w:constellation]] of [[w:Ophiuchus]]. It was discovered by [[w:Charles Messier]] on [[w:May 30]], [[w:1764]].
Located roughly 3° in the sky from the cluster [[w:Messier 10|M10]], M12 is about 16,000 [[w:light-year]]s from Earth and has a spatial diameter of about 75 light-years. The brightest stars of M12 are of 12th [[w:apparent magnitude|magnitude]]. It is rather loosely packed for a globular and was once thought to be a tightly concentrated [[w:open cluster]]. Thirteen [[w:variable star]]s have been recorded in this cluster.
A study published in [[w:2006]] concluded that this cluster has an unusually low number of low mass stars. The authors surmise that they were stripped from the cluster by the gravitational influence of the [[w:Milky Way]].[http://www.eso.org/outreach/press-rel/pr-2006/pr-04-06.html]
<gallery> Image:M12 Hubble.jpg|M12 core by [[w:Hubble Space Telescope|HST]], 3.18&prime; view Image:M12HunterWilson.jpg|M12, courtesy Hunter Wilson Image:ESO-Messier 12-Phot-04a-06.jpg| The Central Part of Messier 12. Credit: [[w:ESO]] </gallery>
==External links== {{commons|Messier 12|Messier 12}} *[http://www.seds.org/messier/m/m012.html Messier 12, SEDS Messier pages] *[http://venus.mporzio.astro.it/~marco/gc/cluster_4.php?ggc=M+12 Messier 12, Galactic Globular Clusters Database page] *[http://www.universetoday.com/am/publish/past_globular_m12.html?822006 'Stolen' stars article at ''Universe Today'']
