{{ Cluster | | name = Messier 18 |image=[[image:Messier18.jpg|200px]] |caption=M18 photo from the [[w:2MASS]] project. | epoch = J2000.0 | class = II,3,p,n | ra = 18<sup>h</sup>&nbsp;19.9<sup>m</sup> | dec = &minus;17° 08&prime; | dist_ly = 4.9 [[w:light year|kly]] | dist_pc = 1.5 kPc | appmag_v = 7.5 | size_v = 9.0&prime; | mass_kg = | mass_msol = | radius_ly = 9 ly | v_hb = | age = 32 million years | notes = | names = NGC 6613 }}
'''Messier 18''' or '''M18''' (also designated '''NGC 6613''') is an [[w:open cluster]] of [[w:star]]s in the [[w:constellation]] [[w:Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]]. It was discovered by [[w:Charles Messier]] in [[w:1764]] and included in his list of [[w:comet]]-like objects. From the perspective of [[w:Earth]], M18 is situated between the [[w:Omega Nebula]] (M17) and the [[w:Sagittarius Star Cloud]] (M24). Its age is estimated at 32 million years.
==External links== {{commons|Messier 18|Messier 18}} * [http://www.seds.org/messier/m/m018.html Messier 18, SEDS Messier pages]
{{Messier Index}}

{{ Cluster | | name = Messier 21 | image = [[image:Messier_object_021.jpg|150px]][ | epoch = J2000.0 | class = I,3,m | ra = 18<sup>h</sup>&nbsp;04.6<sup>m</sup> | dec = &minus;22° 30&prime; | dist_ly = 4.25 [[w:light year|kly]] | dist_pc = 1.3 kPc | appmag_v = 6.5 | size_v = 13.0&prime; | mass_kg = | mass_msol = | radius_ly = | v_hb = | age = 4.6 million years | notes = | names = NGC 6531 }}
'''Messier 21''' or '''M21''' (also designated '''NGC 6531''') is an [[w:open cluster]] of [[w:star]]s in the [[w:constellation]] of [[w:Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]]. It was discovered and catalogued by [[w:Charles Messier]] on [[w:June 5]], [[w:1764]].
M21 is a relatively young cluster of a mere 4.6 million [[w:year]]s of age. It is tightly packed but contains about 57 [[w:star]]s. A few blue giant stars have been identified in the cluster, but Messier 21 is composed mainly of small dim stars. With a magnitude of 6.5, M21 is not visible to the naked eye; however, with the smallest binoculars it can be easily spotted on a dark night.
==External links== * [http://www.seds.org/messier/m/m021.html Messier 21, SEDS Messier pages]
{{Messier Index}}

{{ Cluster | | name = [[w:Messier object|Messier]] 23 | image = [[image:Messier_object_023.jpg|250px]] | epoch = [[w:J2000]] | class = I,2,r | ra = 17<sup>h</sup>&nbsp;56.8<sup>m</sup> | dec = &minus;19° 01&prime; | dist_ly = 2.15 [[w:light year|kly]] | dist_pc = 659 Pc | appmag_v = 6.9 | size_v = 27.0&prime; | mass_kg = | mass_msol = | radius_ly = 8 | v_hb = | age = 220 million years{{Fact|date=February 2007}} | constellation = [[w:Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]] | notes = | names = NGC 6494 }}
'''Messier 23''' (also known as '''NGC 6494''') is an [[w:open cluster]] in the [[w:constellation]] [[w:Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]]. It was discovered by [[w:Charles Messier]] on [[w:June 20]], [[w:1764]].
M23 is at a distance of about 2,150 [[w:light-year]]s away from [[w:Earth]], its radius is around 15-20 [[w:light years]]. There are some 150 identified members in this cluster, the brightest being of [[w:apparent magnitude|magnitude]] 9.2. M23 can be found with a modestly sized [[w:telescope]] in the rich starfields of the Sagittarius [[w:Milky Way]].
==External links== * [http://www.seds.org/messier/m/m023.html Messier 23, SEDS Messier pages]
{{Messier Index}}

{{ Cluster | | name = Messier 25 | image = [[image:M25 48 06.jpg|250px]]Sketch of the cluster | epoch = J2000.0 | class = IV,3,r | ra = 18<sup>h</sup>&nbsp;31.6<sup>m</sup> | dec = &minus;19° 15&prime; | dist_ly = 2.0 [[w:light year|kly]] | dist_pc = 613 Pc | appmag_v = 4.6 | size_v = 32.0&prime; | mass_kg = | mass_msol = | radius_ly = 10 | v_hb = | age = 90 million years | notes = | names = IC 4725 }}
'''Open Cluster M25''' (also known as '''Messier Object 25''' or '''IC 4725''') is an [[w:open cluster]] in the [[w:constellation]] [[w:Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]]. It was discovered by [[w:Philippe Loys de Chéseaux]] in [[w:1745]] and included in [[w:Charles Messier]]'s list in [[w:1764]].
M25 is at a distance of about 2,000 [[w:light-year]]s away from [[w:Earth]]. The spatial dimension of this cluster is about 19 [[w:light year]]s across. A [[w:Cepheid variable|Delta Cephei]] type [[w:variable star]] designated ''U Sagittarii'' is a member of this cluster.
==External links== * [http://www.seds.org/messier/m/m025.html Messier 25, SEDS Messier pages]
{{Messier Index}}

{{ Cluster | |image=[[image:Messier_object_026.jpg]] | name = Messier 26 | epoch = J2000.0 | class = II,2,r | ra = 18<sup>h</sup>&nbsp;45.2<sup>m</sup> | dec = &minus;09° 24&prime; | constellation = [[w:Scutum]] | dist_ly = 5.0 [[w:light year|kly]] | dist_pc = 1534 pc | appmag_v = 8.0 | size_v = 15.0&prime; | mass_kg = | mass_msol = | radius_ly = 22 ly | v_hb = | age = 89 million years | notes = | names = NGC 6694 }}
'''Open Cluster M26''' (also known as '''Messier Object 26''' or '''NGC 6694''') is an [[w:open cluster]] in the [[w:constellation]] [[w:Scutum]]. It was discovered by [[w:Charles Messier]] in [[w:1764]].
M26 spans about 22 [[w:light year]]s across and is at a distance of 5,000 light years from the [[w:Earth]]. The brightest star is of [[w:apparent magnitude|magnitude]] 11.9 and the age of this cluster has been calculated to be 89 million years. An interesting feature of M26 is a region of low [[w:star]] density near the nucleus, most likely caused by an obscuring cloud of [[w:interstellar matter]] between us and the cluster.
==External links== * [http://www.seds.org/messier/m/m026.html Messier 26, SEDS Messier pages]
