{{ Globular cluster | | name = [[w:Messier object|Messier]] 30 | image = [[image:Messier 30 Hubble WikiSky.jpg|280px]] | caption = M30 by [[w:Hubble Space Telescope]]; 3.5&prime; view | credit = [[w:NASA]]/[[w:STScI]]/[[w:WikiSky]] | epoch = [[w:J2000]] | class = | ra = {{RA|21|40|22.03}}<ref name="simbad">{{cite web | title=SIMBAD Astronomical Database | work=Results for NGC 7099 | url=http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/Simbad | accessdate=2006-11-16}}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|-23|10|44.6}}<ref name="simbad" /> | dist_ly = 26 [[w:light-year|kly]]{{Fact|date=February 2007}} | dist_pc = 9 [[w:parsec|kpc]] | appmag_v = +7.7<ref name="simbad" /> | size_v = | constellation = [[w:Capricornus constellation|Capricornus]] | mass_kg = | mass_msol = | radius_ly = | v_hb = | age = ? Gyr | notes = | names = M30, [[w:New General Catalogue|NGC]] 7099, GCl 122<ref name="simbad" /> }} {{commonscat|Messier 30}}
'''Messier 30''' (also known as '''M30''' or '''NGC 7099''') is a [[w:globular cluster]] in the [[w:Capricornus constellation]]. It was discovered by [[w:Charles Messier]] in [[w:1764]]. M30 is at a distance of about 26,000 [[w:light-year]]s away from [[w:Earth]].
