{{ Cluster | | name = Messier 36 | image = [[image:M36_2mass.jpg|250px]] |caption = Open cluster M36 seen in infrared light., courtesy of: [http://www.ipac.caltech.edu/2mass/gallery/messiercat.html] | epoch = J2000.0 | class = I | constellation = [[w:Auriga (constellation)|Auriga]] | ra = 5<sup>h</sup>&nbsp;36<sup>m</sup>&nbsp;12<sup>s</sup> | dec = +34° 08&prime; 4&Prime; | dist_ly = 4.1 [[w:light year|kly]] | dist_pc = 1.3 [[w:parsec|kpc]] | appmag_v = 6.3 | size_v = 12&prime; | mass_kg = | mass_msol = | radius_ly = 14 ly | v_hb = | age = 25 [[w:Julian year (astronomy)|Ma]] | notes = | names = [[w:NGC 1960]] }}
'''Open Cluster M36''' (also known as '''Messier Object 36''', '''Messier 36''', '''M36''', or '''NGC 1960''') is an [[w:open cluster]] in the [[w:Auriga constellation]]. It was discovered by [[w:Giovanni Batista Hodierna]] before [[w:1654]]. M36 is at a distance of about 4,100 [[w:light year]]s away from [[w:Earth]] and is about 14 light years across. There are at least sixty members in the cluster. The cluster is very similar to the [[w:Pleiades (star cluster)|Pleiades]] cluster (M45), and if it were the same distance from Earth it would be of similar magnitude.
==External links== * [http://www.seds.org/messier/m/m036.html Messier 36, SEDS Messier pages]
{{Messier Index}}

{{ Cluster | | name = Messier 37 | image = [[image:M37a.jpg|250px]] |caption = M37 open cluster, source: [http://www.noao.edu/ NOAO] | epoch = J2000.0 | class = I | constellation = [[w:Auriga (constellation)|Auriga]] | ra = 5<sup>h</sup>&nbsp;52<sup>m</sup>&nbsp;19<sup>s</sup> | dec = +32° 33&prime; 2&Prime; | dist_ly = 4.4 [[w:light year|kly]] | dist_pc = 1.3 [[w:parsec|kpc]] | appmag_v = 6.2 | size_v = 24&prime; | mass_kg = | mass_msol = | radius_ly = 20-25 ly | v_hb = | age = 300 [[w:Julian year (astronomy)|Ma]] | notes = | names = [[w:NGC 2099]] }}
'''Messier 37''' (also known as ''M37'' or ''[[w:New General Catalogue|NGC]] 2099'') is the richest [[w:open cluster]] in the [[w:constellation]] [[w:Auriga (constellation)|Auriga]]. It was discovered by [[w:Giovanni Batista Hodierna]] before [[w:1654]].
[[w:Messier object|Messier]] 37 is the brightest of the three open clusters in Auriga. M37 was missed by [[w:Le Gentil]] when he rediscovered M36 and M38 in 1749. [[w:Charles Messier]] independently rediscovered M37 in September of [[w:1764]] but all three clusters were recorded by Hodierna before 1654. All three clusters were generally unknown until [[w:1984]].
M37 is roughly 300 million years old and contains over 500 stars with roughly 150 stars brighter than [[w:apparent magnitude|magnitude]] 12.5. M37 also contains at least a dozen [[w:red giants]] with the hottest [[w:main sequence]] star of [[w:spectral type]] B9V. Its distance is between 3,600 to 4,700 [[w:light years]] and the apparent diameter of 24' corresponds to a [[w:linear extension]] of about 20 to 25 light years. It is classified as [[w:Robert Julius Trumpler|Trumpler]] type I,1,r or I,2,r.
==External links== * [http://www.seds.org/messier/m/m037.html Messier 37, SEDS Messier pages]
{{Messier Index}}

{{ Cluster | | name = Messier 38 | image = [[image:M38a.jpg|250px]] |caption = M38 open cluster, source: [[w:NOAO]] | epoch = J2000.0 | class = II | constellation = [[w:Auriga (constellation)|Auriga]] | ra = 5<sup>h</sup>&nbsp;28<sup>m</sup>&nbsp;42<sup>s</sup> | dec = +35° 51&prime; 18&Prime; | dist_ly = 4.2 [[w:light year|kly]] | dist_pc = 1.3 [[w:parsec|kpc]] | appmag_v = 7.4 | size_v = 21&prime; | mass_kg = | mass_msol = ? | radius_ly = 25 ly | v_hb = -1.5 | age = 220 [[w:Julian year (astronomy)|Ma]] | notes = | names = [[w:NGC 1912]] }}
'''Messier 38''' (also known as '''M38''' or '''NGC 1912''') is an [[w:open cluster]] in the [[w:Auriga constellation]].
It was discovered by [[w:Giovanni Batista Hodierna]] before [[w:1654]] and independently found by [[w:Le Gentil]] in [[w:1749]]. [[w:M36]] and [[w:M37]], also discovered by Hodierna, are grouped together with [[w:M38]] at a distance of about 3,420 [[w:light year]]s away from [[w:Earth]].<ref name=majaess2007>Majaess D. J., Turner D., Lane D. (2007). [http://lanl.arxiv.org/abs/0710.2900 ''In Search of Possible Associations between Planetary Nebulae and Open Clusters''], PASP, 119, 1349</ref>
The cluster's brightest stars form a pattern resembling the Greek letter [[w:Pi (letter)|Pi]] or, according to Webb, an "oblique cross." At its distance of 4,200 light years, its angular diameter of about 20' corresponds to about 25 light years, similar to that of its more distant neighbor M37. It is of intermediate age (about 220 million years, according to ''Sky Catalog 2000'') and features a yellow giant of [[w:apparent magnitude]] +7.9 and [[w:spectral type]] G0 as its brightest member. This corresponds to an [[w:absolute magnitude]] of -1.5, or a luminosity of 900 suns. For comparison, the [[w:Sun]] would appear as a faint magnitude +15.3 star from the distance of M38.
==Components== {| class=wikitable |- bgcolor="#CDC9C9;" ! colspan="1" | NAME || [[w:Right ascension]] || [[w:Declination]] || [[w:Spectral type]] |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | [[w:HD 35519]] || 05<sup>h</sup> 26<sup>m</sup> 54.3176<sup>s</sup> || +35° 27' 26.181'' || K2 |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 2 || || || B5II-III |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 3 || || || |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 4 || 05<sup>h</sup> 28<sup>m</sup> 35.39<sup>s</sup> || +35° 52' 51.2'' || A0V |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 5 || 05<sup>h</sup> 28<sup>m</sup> 50.73<sup>s</sup> || +35° 46' 47.2'' || A0Vn |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 6 || 05<sup>h</sup> 28<sup>m</sup> 10.46<sup>s</sup> || +35° 55' 26.0'' || A0:V |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 7 || 05<sup>h</sup> 28<sup>m</sup> 34.25<sup>s</sup> || +35° 53' 29.7'' || A2V |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 11 || || || |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 19 || || || K2IIIb |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 104 || || || G5III |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 SS G2 || || || || |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 128 || || || K0III |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 SS G4 || || || A5:V |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 153 || || || K0V |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 SS G3 || || || A3V |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 160 || || || K1IV |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 161 || || || G5V |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 171 || || || G7IV |- bgcolor="#FFFAFA" | NGC 1912 HOAG 172 || || || |- |}
