{{Infobox galaxy | name = [[w:Messier object|Messier]] 66 | image = [[image:Sig05-016.jpg|250px]] |caption = M66 as observed with the [[w:Spitzer Space Telescope]] as part of the [[w:Spitzer Infrared Nearby Galaxy Survey|SINGS]]. The image is a four-channel false-color composite, where blue indicates emission at 3.6 [[w:micrometre|micrometers]], green corresponds to 4.5 micrometers, and red to 5.8 and 8.0 micrometers. The contribution from starlight (measured at 3.6 micrometers) in this picture has been subtracted from the 5.8 and 8 micrometer images to enhance the visibility of the [[w:polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]] emissions. | epoch = [[w:J2000]] | type = SAB(s)b<ref name="ned">{{cite web | title=NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database | work=Results for NGC 3627 | url=http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/ | accessdate=2006-08-31 }}</ref> | ra = {{RA|11|20|15.0}}<ref name="ned" /> | dec = {{DEC|+12|59|30}}<ref name="ned" /> | dist_ly = 36 +/- 5.0 M[[w:Light-year|ly]] (11.0 +/- 1.5 M[[w:Parsec|pc]] | z = 0.002425 (727 ± 3 km/[[w:second|s]])<ref name="ned" /> | appmag_v = 8.9<ref name="devaucouleursetal1991">{{cite book | author=G. de Vaucouleurs, A. de Vaucouleurs, H. G. Corwin, R. J. Buta, G. Paturel, P. Fouque | year=1991 | title=Third Reference Catalogue of Bright Galaxies | publisher=Springer-Verlag | location=New York}}</ref> | size_v = 9.1&prime; &times; 4.2&prime;<ref name="ned" /> | constellation name = [[w:Leo (constellation)|Leo]] | notes = Galaxy in the [[w:Leo Triplet]] | names = [[w:New General Catalogue|NGC]] 3627, [[w:Uppsala General Catalogue|UGC]] 6346, [[w:Principal Galaxies Catalogue|PGC]] 34695, [[w:Atlas of Peculiar Galaxies|Arp]] 16<ref name="ned" /> }}
'''Messier 66''' (also known as ''NGC 3627'') is an [[w:intermediate spiral galaxy]] about 36 million [[w:light-year]]s away in the [[w:constellation]] [[w:Leo (constellation)|Leo]]. It was discovered by [[w:Charles Messier]] in [[w:1780]]. M66 is about 95 thousand light-years across<ref>36.2 mly &times; tan( 9&prime;.1 ) = ~96 kly. radius</ref> with striking dust lanes and bright star clusters along sweeping spiral arms.<ref name="Zhangetal1993">{{cite journal | author=Zhang, Xiaolei; Wright, Melvyn; Alexander, Paul | title=High-Resolution CO and H i Observations of the Interacting Galaxy NGC 3627 | journal=Astrophysical Journal | year=1993 | volume=418 | pages=100 | url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?bibcode=1993ApJ...418..100Z | doi=10.1086/173374 }}</ref> M66 is part of the famous [[w:Leo Triplet]], a small [[w:group of galaxies]] that also includes [[w:Messier 65|M65]] and [[w:NGC 3628]].
==History== [[image:Phot-33c-03-fullres.jpg|left|thumb|250px|The colour-composite image of the Spiral galaxy M 66 (or NGC 3627)]] [[image:M66HunterWilson.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Messier 66 in [[w:Leo]] with amateur telescope.]]
Gravitational interaction from its past encounter with neighboring NGC 3628 has resulted in:
* An extremely high central mass concentration; * A high [[w:molecular mass|molecular]] to [[w:atomic mass]] ratio; * A resolved noncorotating clump of [[w:H I]] material apparently removed from one of the [[w:spiral arm]]s.
This third result shows up visually as an extremely prominent and unusual spiral arm and dust lane structures as originally noted in the [[w:Atlas of Peculiar Galaxies]].<ref name="Zhangetal1993" />
==External links== * [http://www.seds.org/messier/m/m066.html SEDS: Spiral Galaxy M66] * [http://ryutao.main.jp/english/st2k_m66_m300.html Spiral Galaxy M66]
