{{Infobox galaxy | name = [[w:Messier object|Messier]] 89<ref name="tonryetal2001">{{cite journal | author=J. L. Tonry, A. Dressler, J. P. Blakeslee, E. A. Ajhar, A. B. Fletcher, G. A. Luppino, M. R. Metzger, C. B. Moore | title=The SBF Survey of Galaxy Distances. IV. SBF Magnitudes, Colors, and Distances | journal=Astrophysical Journal | year=2001 | volume=546 | issue=2 | pages=681–693 | url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2001ApJ...546..681T | doi=10.1086/318301 }}</ref> | image = | caption = Messier 89 on [[w:Digitized Sky Survey|DSS2]] all sky survey. | epoch = [[w:J2000]] | constellation name = [[w:Virgo (constellation)|Virgo]] | ra = {{RA|12|35|39.8}}<ref name="ned">{{cite web | title=NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database | work=Results for NGC 4552 | url=http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/ | accessdate=2006-10-24 }}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|+12|33|23}}<ref name="ned" /> | appmag_v = 10.73<ref name="ned" /> | type = E<ref name="ned" />, [[w:LINER]]<ref name="ned" />, [[w:Seyfert galaxy|H<sub>II</sub>Sy2]]<ref name="ned" /> | names = [[w:New General Catalogue|NGC]] 4552,<ref name="ned" /> [[w:Uppsala General Catalogue|UGC]] 7760,<ref name="ned" /> [[w:Principal Galaxies Catalogue|PGC]] 41968<ref name="ned" /> }}
'''Messier 89''' ('''M89''' for short, also known as '''NGC 4552''') is an [[w:elliptical galaxy]] in the constellation [[w:Virgo (constellation)|Virgo]]. It was discovered by [[w:Charles Messier]] on [[w:March 18]] [[w:1781]]. M89 is a member of the [[w:Virgo Cluster|Virgo Cluster of galaxies]].<ref>[http://www.seds.org/messier/m/m089.html Elliptical Galaxy M89 @ SEDS Messier pages]</ref>
== Unusual features == Current observations indicate that M89 may be nearly perfectly [[w:Sphere|spherical]] in shape. This would be unusual as all other known elliptic galaxies are relatively elongated [[w:ellipsoids]].{{Fact|date=February 2007}} However, it is possible that the galaxy is oriented in such a way that it appears spherical to an observer on Earth but is in fact elliptical.
The galaxy also features a surrounding structure of gas and dust extending up to 150,000 light-years from the galaxy and jets of heated particles that extend 100,000 light-years outwards, indications that it may have once been an active [[w:quasar]] or [[w:radio galaxy]].<ref>[http://www.seasky.org/astronomy/astronomy_messier_81to90.html Messier Objects 81-90 @ Sea and Sky]</ref>
M89 also has a large population of [[w:globular cluster]]s as compared to the [[w:Milky Way]]'s 150-200, a [[w:2006]] survey out to 10&prime; of its core estimates that there are 2,000 ± 700 globulars within 25&prime; of M89.<ref name="Tamuraetal2006">{{cite journal | author=Tamura, Naoyuki; Sharples, Ray M.; Arimoto, Nobuo; Onodera, Masato; Ohta, Kouji; Yamada, Yoshihiko | title=A Subaru/Suprime-Cam wide-field survey of globular cluster populations around M87 - I. Observation, data analysis and luminosity function | journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society | volume=Online Early | year=2006 | url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/cgi-bin/nph-bib_query?doi=10.1111%2Fj.1365-2966.2006.11067.x | doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2006.11067.x | pages=588 }}</ref>
