{{Infobox galaxy | name = [[w:Messier object|Messier]] 98 | image = [[image:M-98.jpg|350px]] |caption = Messier 98 | epoch = [[w:J2000]] | type = SAB(s)ab<ref name="ned">{{cite web | title=NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database | work=Results for Messier 98 | url=http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/ | accessdate=2006-11-18}}</ref> | ra = {{RA|12|13|48.3}}<ref name="ned" /> | dec = {{DEC|+14|54|01}}<ref name="ned" /> | dist_ly = [[w:1 E23 m|60]] [[w:light-year|Mly]]{{Fact|date=February 2007}} | z = -142 ± 4 km/[[w:second|s]]<ref name="ned" /> | appmag_v = 11.0<ref name="ned" /> | size_v = 9&prime;.8 &times; 2&prime;.8<ref name="ned" /> | constellation name = [[w:Coma Berenices]] | names = [[w:New General Catalogue|NGC]] 4192, [[w:Uppsala General Catalogue|UGC]] 7231, [[w:Principal Galaxies Catalogue|PGC]] 39028<ref name="ned" /> }}
'''Messier 98''' (also known as ''M98'' or ''NGC 4192'') is an intermediate [[w:spiral galaxy]] about [[w:1 E23 m|60 million]] [[w:light-year]]s away in the [[w:constellation]] [[w:Coma Berenices]]. It was discovered by [[w:Pierre Méchain]] in [[w:1781]].
==Virgo Cluster membership== Messier 98 is a member of the [[w:Virgo Cluster]], which is a large, relatively nearby [[w:cluster of galaxies]].<ref name="binggelietal1985">{{cite journal | author= B. Binggeli, A. Sandage, G. A. Tammann | title=Studies of the Virgo Cluster. II - A catalog of 2096 galaxies in the Virgo Cluster area | journal=Astronomical Journal | year=1985 | volume=90 | pages=1681–1759 | url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1985AJ.....90.1681B | doi= 10.1086/113874 }}</ref>
