{{Infobox galaxy | name = [[w:Messier object|Messier]] 100 | image = [[image:M100.jpg|250px]] | credit = [[w:ESO]] [[w:VLT]] view revealing complex spiral arm structure | constellation name = [[w:Coma Berenices]]<ref name="sinnott1988">{{cite book | author=R. W. Sinnott, editor | title= The Complete New General Catalogue and Index Catalogue of Nebulae and Star Clusters by J. L. E. Dreyer | year=1988 | publisher=Sky Publishing Corporation and Cambridge University Press | isbn=0-933-34651-4}}</ref> | epoch = [[w:J2000]] | type = SAB(s)bc<ref name="ned">{{cite web | title=NASA/IPAC Extragalactic Database | work=Results for NGC 4321 | url=http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/ | accessdate=2006-08-31}}</ref> | ra = {{RA|12|22|54.9}}<ref name="ned" /> | dec = {{DEC|+15|49|21}}<ref name="ned" /> | dist_ly = 52.5 [[w:light-year|Mly]]<ref name="xiv">{{cite web | title=Pattern Speeds BIMA-SONG Galaxies with Molecule-Dominated ISMs Using the Tremaine-Weinberg Method | work=(Ferrarese et al. 1996) | url=http://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0406426 | accessdate=2006-08-31}}</ref> | z = 1571 ± 1 km/[[w:second|s]]<ref name="ned" /> | appmag_v = 10.1<ref name="ned" /> | size_v = 7&prime;.4 &times; 6&prime;.3<ref name="ned" /> | names = [[w:New General Catalogue|NGC]] 4321 }} '''Messier 100''' (also known as ''[[w:New General Catalogue|NGC]] 4321'') is a [[w:spiral galaxy]] about 52.5 million [[w:light-year]]s away in the [[w:constellation]] [[w:Coma Berenices]]. It was discovered by [[w:Pierre Méchain]] in [[w:1781]]. It is one of the brightest galaxies in the [[w:Virgo cluster]]. Five [[w:supernova]]e have been identified in M100: [[w:SN 1901B]], [[w:SN 1914A]], [[w:SN 1959E]], [[w:SN 1979C]] and [[w:SN 2006X]]. M100 also has a [[w:satellite galaxy]] named [[w:NGC 4323]].
